Problem Statement Key-Points¶

The education market is markedly changing and growing in demand in the Online Education sector. The supply side is thus incentivized to increase its investment in market research and analysis in order to improve its customer targeting strategy.

Additionaly, companies need to take into account that they interact with two-sided markets through social media marketing and highly rely on so-called leads customers.

The goals are to:

  1. Perform customer analysis i.e., EDA
  2. Build an ML model that predicts the probability for a given lead to be converted into a paid customer i.e., classify leads into future paid customers and non-customers
  3. Socio-economically and demographically identify leads classified as future customers

We present this Conversion Rate Optimization project following the above sections.

General Description of the Dataset¶

The dataset displays 4612 rows i.e., 4612 leads and 15 columns (1 ID, 13 predictors and one target).

Data Types and Missing Values¶

Overall, the categorical variables and are stored as object. 'Status' is stored as an integer even though it is a categorical variable i.e., dummy. There are no missing values.

  1. The dataset includes general information about the lead:
  • their age
  • they current occupation
  • the type of their first interaction with ExtraaLearn
  • the percentage of completed profile on a website or mobile application
  1. The dataset also includes specific website-related information:
  • the number of visits
  • the total time spent
  • the average number of pages viewed
  • the type of the last activity with a representative on the website
  • the last interaction between the lead and ExtraaLearn
  1. The dataset also includes specific media-related information:
  • whether the lead had seen an ad in the newspapper
  • whether the lead had seen an ad in the magazine
  • whether the lead had seen an ad on digital platforms
  • whether the lead had seen an ad in educational channel
  1. The dataset also includes specific direct communication-related information:
  • the type of activity on the phone with a representative
  • whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn through reference
  1. The target variable:
  • whether the lead was converted to a paid customer or not

Disclaimer: at the date of creation of the project, the columns last_activity, Email Activity and Phone Activity were missing from the dataset

We further explore the bi-modality of the distribution of time spent on website.

Specifically, we use a Gaussian Mixture Models (GMMs) to fit a mixture of Gaussian distributions to the data and determine whether it comes from a single distribution or multiple distributions. GMMs are a probabilistic model commonly used for clustering and density estimation tasks, including identifying subpopulations within a dataset.

In [ ]:
# Extract the column containing our time data
data = df['time_spent_on_website']

# Fit Gaussian Mixture Model with different number of components
n_components = np.arange(1, 3)
models = [GaussianMixture(n, covariance_type='full', random_state=0).fit(data.values.reshape(-1, 1)) for n in n_components]
bic_scores = [model.bic(data.values.reshape(-1, 1)) for model in models]

# Determine the optimal number of components using the Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC)
optimal_n_components = n_components[np.argmin(bic_scores)]

# Fit GMM with the optimal number of components
gmm = GaussianMixture(n_components=optimal_n_components, covariance_type='full', random_state=0)
gmm.fit(data.values.reshape(-1, 1))

# Plot histogram of the data
plt.hist(data, bins=50, density=True, alpha=0.5, color='gray')

# Plot each component of the GMM
x = np.linspace(data.min(), data.max(), 1000)
for i in range(optimal_n_components):
    y = norm.pdf(x, gmm.means_[i, 0], np.sqrt(gmm.covariances_[i, 0, 0]))
    plt.plot(x, y, label=f'Component {i+1}')

plt.legend()
plt.title(f'Gaussian Mixture Model with {optimal_n_components} components')
plt.xlabel('Value')
plt.ylabel('Density')
plt.show()

Non Linear Analysis¶

We explore the following technique:

Mutual Information

Mutual Information measures the amount of information that knowing the value of one variable provides about another variable. It can capture both linear and non-linear dependencies.

Mututal Information¶

Mutual information is a measure of the amount of information one random variable contains about another random variable. It is used to quantify the dependence between the two variables. The formula for mutual information

$$I(X;Y)$$

between two discrete random variables $$X$$ and $$Y$$ is given by:

$$ I(X;Y)=\int_{y Y} \int_{x X} p(x,y) . log(\frac{p(x,y)}{p(x)p(y)}) dx dy)$$

where:

$p(x,y)$ is the joint probability mass function of $X$ and $Y$,

$p(x)$ is the marginal probability mass function of $X$,

$p(y)$ is the marginal probability mass function of $Y$.

Important Note

In the context of feature selection and mutual information regression, the mutual information between a feature and the target variable is calculated to estimate the information gain about the target provided by that feature.

It's important to note that mutual information is a symmetric measure, meaning

$$ I(X;Y)=I(Y;X) $$

. Also, it is non-negative, and higher values indicate stronger dependencies between the variables.

The concept of mutual information is related to, but distinct from, Fisher information. Fisher information is a concept from statistics used in the context of estimating parameters in a statistical model. It is related to the variance of the score function (derivative of the log-likelihood function) with respect to the parameter. While both mutual information and Fisher information involve the concept of information, they serve different purposes and are applied in different contexts within statistics and information theory.

In practice, when estimating mutual information from data, you might use kernel density estimation (KDE) or other methods to approximate the probability density functions. The goal is to estimate the joint and marginal distributions from the observed data and then apply the mutual information formula.

In [ ]:
# Identify numerical columns
numerical_columns = df.select_dtypes(include=['int', 'float']).columns

# Select the target variable
y = df["status"]

# Initialize an empty dictionary to store KDE models for each numerical feature
kde_models = {}

# Fit KDE models for each numerical feature
for column in numerical_columns:
    kde = KernelDensity(bandwidth=1.0, kernel='gaussian')  # You can adjust the bandwidth and kernel as needed
    kde.fit(df[column].values.reshape(-1, 1))
    kde_models[column] = kde

# Calculate mutual information using KDE-based PDFs
mutual_info_scores = {}
for column in numerical_columns:
    kde = kde_models[column]
    log_density_x = kde.score_samples(df[column].values.reshape(-1, 1))
    log_density_y = kde.score_samples(y.values.reshape(-1, 1))
    mi = np.mean(log_density_x + log_density_y - kde.score_samples(df[column].values.reshape(-1, 1)))
    mutual_info_scores[column] = mi

# Display mutual information scores
print("Mutual Information Scores:")
print(mutual_info_scores)

Mutual Information Scores:
{'age': -161.94074402054937, 'website_visits': -2.4411362252046316, 'time_spent_on_website': -4.031832578410107, 'page_views_per_visit': -2.493606427163135, 'status': -1.1030207801375402}

The negative MI values indicate that the joint information shared between variables is less than the information contained in the product of their marginal distributions. In other words, knowing one variable provides less information about the other variable than would be expected if they were independent. However, the relative difference in MI values between different pairs of variables is still informative.

When comparing MI values across different pairs of variables, the relative differences are often more informative than the absolute values themselves. Negative MI values may still indicate meaningful relationships or dependencies between variables, especially when comparing them within the same dataset or analysis.

We see in particular that age contains way more information about status than the other variable in absolute value.

kmedoids = KMedoids(n_clusters=num_clusters, random_state=42)

# Fit K-Medoids model

# Visualize clustering results

plt.title('Visualization with K-Medoids Clusters')

# Show the plot

We see that age and time spent on website stratify the data. Duration under 500 minutes encompass 4 clusters out of 7, across the entire age spectrum.

Machine Learning¶

We will be using different metrics functions defined in sklearn like RMSE, MAE, 2, Adjusted 2, and MAPE for regression model evaluation. We will define a function to calculate these metrics. The mean absolute percentage error (MAPE) measures the accuracy of predictions as a percentage and can be calculated as the average absolute percentage error for all data points. The absolute percentage error is defined as the predicted value minus actual value divided by actual value. It works best if there are no extreme values in the data and none of the actual values are 0.

Benchmark ML Models¶

In [ ]:
# Function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model
def model_performance_classification(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable (binary)
    """

    pred_probs = model.predict(predictors)  # Predict probabilities
    y_pred = (pred_probs > 0.5).astype(int)  # Convert probabilities to binary predictions

    accuracy = accuracy_score(target, y_pred)          # To compute accuracy
    precision = precision_score(target, y_pred)        # To compute precision
    recall = recall_score(target, y_pred)              # To compute recall
    f1 = f1_score(target, y_pred)                      # To compute F1 score
    confusion_mat = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)   # To compute confusion matrix

    # Creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": accuracy,
            "Precision": precision,
            "Recall": recall,
            "F1 Score": f1,
            "Confusion Matrix": [confusion_mat],
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Decision Trees¶

What is a Decision Tree?

Decision Trees are a type of supervised machine learning algorithm that can be used for both classification and regression tasks. They are often used in business and industry to make decisions based on data, and are particularly useful for tasks that require decision-making based on a set of conditions.

How does a Decision Tree work?

A Decision Tree works by recursively splitting the dataset into smaller subsets based on the feature that provides the most information gain at each step. This process continues until the subsets are as pure as possible, meaning that they contain as few mixed class labels as possible, or until a stopping criterion is met (e.g., when a maximum depth is reached).

$$\large Information\ Gain = Entropy\ before\ split - Entropy\ after\ split$$

where, $$\large Entropy = -\sum_{i=1}^{c} p_i \log_2 p_i$$

Here, $p$ is the proportion of positive instances in the subset.

The goal of the algorithm is to find the tree that provides the best predictions on the training data, while also being as simple and interpretable as possible.

Let's visualize the decision tree and examine the tree's decision rules. Visualizing a Decision Tree can help you understand how the algorithm works and interpret its predictions. Visualizing the tree can help us to:

  • Identify the root node: The first node at the top of the tree is called the root node. It represents the entire dataset and is used to split the data into two or more homogeneous subsets. Here, the root node splits the lead data set according to their medium of first interaction (website or not).

  • Identify the internal nodes: The nodes that are not leaf nodes are called internal nodes. They represent a decision or a test on a feature and are used to split the data into smaller subsets based on the feature value.

  • Identify the leaf nodes: The nodes at the bottom of the tree are called leaf nodes. They represent the output or the class label of the data after going through all the splits in the tree.

  • Follow a path from the root to a leaf node: To interpret a decision tree, we can follow a path from the root node to a leaf node. Along the path, we can see the tests performed on the features, and based on the test results, the data is split into smaller subsets. The order in which variables are considered to make a prediction is: website as first medium of interaction, time spent on the website, activity last recorded, referral and profile completeness.

  • Analyze the feature importance: We can analyze the feature importance by looking at the splits in the tree. The features used to split the data at the top of the tree are the most important features, as they have the highest impact on the decision.

  • Analyze the class distribution: We can analyze the class distribution at the leaf nodes to understand how the decision tree predicts the class labels. If the majority of the samples in a leaf node belong to a particular class, the decision tree predicts that class for the new data.

  • Explain the decision: Finally, we can explain the decision made by the decision tree by summarizing the path taken from the root to the leaf node and the class label predicted at the leaf node. We can also explain the importance of the features used in the decision and how they influence the final prediction.

We will limit the decision tree's depth to two so that we can visualize it better.

Bagging Classifier¶

What is a Bagging Regressor?

Bagging (short for Bootstrap Aggregating) is an ensemble learning technique that involves training multiple models on different subsets of the training data and then combining their predictions. The idea is to reduce variance and overfitting by averaging the predictions of many models.

A Bagging Regressor is a type of Bagging algorithm used for regression tasks. It involves training multiple regression models (e.g., Decision Trees) on different subsets of the training data and then combining their predictions by taking the average.

How does a Bagging Regressor work?

The Bagging Regressor works by generating multiple subsets of the training data by randomly selecting data points with replacement (i.e., allowing the same data point to be selected more than once in the same subset). Each subset is used to train a separate regression model, and the predictions of these models are combined by taking their average.

The idea behind this approach is that by training multiple models on different subsets of the data, we can reduce the variance and overfitting of the final model, while still maintaining the same bias as a single model trained on the entire dataset.

Random Forest¶

What is a Random Forest?

Random Forest is another ensemble learning technique that combines multiple Decision Trees to create a more robust and accurate model. Like Bagging, it involves training multiple models on different subsets of the training data, but with an additional twist: at each split in the tree, only a random subset of the available features is considered for splitting.

This helps to reduce the correlation between the trees in the forest and improves their overall accuracy.

How does a Random Forest work?

A Random Forest works by training multiple Decision Trees on different subsets of the training data, and then combining their predictions by taking their average. The key difference from Bagging is that at each split in the tree, only a random subset of the features is considered for splitting.

The algorithm works as follows:

  • Generate multiple random subsets of the training data (with replacement).
  • For each subset, train a Decision Tree on a random subset of the features.
  • Make predictions for new data by averaging the predictions of all the trees in the forest.

The number of trees in the forest and the number of features considered at each split are hyperparameters that can be tuned to optimize the performance of the model.

The Random Forest algorithm doesn't have any specific equations, but it involves training multiple Decision Trees on different subsets of the training data with a random subset of the features considered at each split.

AdaBoost¶

What is Adaboost?

Adaboost (short for Adaptive Boosting) is a type of boosting algorithm that combines multiple weak classifiers to create a stronger classifier. A weak classifier is a classifier that performs only slightly better than random guessing.

How does Adaboost work?

  • Adaboost works by training multiple weak classifiers on different subsets of the training data, and then combining their predictions to make a final prediction. The algorithm works as follows:

  • Assign equal weights to all the training examples.

  • Train a weak classifier on a subset of the training data.
  • Increase the weights of the misclassified examples.
  • Train another weak classifier on the same subset of data but with the weights adjusted to give more importance to the misclassified examples.
  • Repeat steps 3-4 for a specified number of iterations or until the error rate is sufficiently low.
  • Combine the predictions of all the weak classifiers to make a final prediction.

The key idea behind Adaboost is that by giving more weight to the misclassified examples, the algorithm can focus on the examples that are more difficult to classify and improve its overall accuracy.

The Adaboost algorithm involves computing the weighted error rate of each weak classifier and using it to update the weights of the training examples. The equation for computing the weighted error rate is:

$$\large \epsilon_t = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{N} w_{t,i} \cdot \mathrm{I\!I}(y_i \neq h_t(x_i))}{\sum_{i=1}^{N} w_{t,i}}$$

Here, $w_i$ is the weight of the $i_{th}$ training example, $y_i$ is the true label of the $i_{th}$ example, $h(x_i)$ is the prediction of the weak classifier for the $i_{th}$ example, and the sum is over all the training examples.

The weight of the weak classifier is then computed as:

$$\large \alpha_t = \frac{1}{2} \ln \left( \frac{1 - \epsilon_t}{\epsilon_t} \right)$$

where $\alpha_t$ is the weight of the $t_{th}$ weak learner in the final model, and $\epsilon_t$ is the weighted error of the $t_{th}$ weak learner.

Finally, the weights of the training examples are updated as follows:

$$\large w_i \gets w_i \exp(-\alpha y_i h(x_i))$$

Here, $exp()$ is the exponential function, $y_i$ is the true label of the $i_{th}$ example, $h(x_i)$ is the prediction of the weak classifier for the $i_{th}$ example, and the sum is over all the training examples.

Gradient Boosting Classifier¶

What is Gradient Boosting?

Gradient Boosting is another boosting algorithm that combines multiple weak learners to create a strong learner. The difference between Adaboost and Gradient Boosting is that the former assigns different weights to different data points, while the latter fits the model to the residual errors of the previous model.

How does Gradient Boosting work?

Gradient Boosting works by sequentially adding weak learners to the model and updating the weights of the training examples based on the residual errors of the previous models. The algorithm works as follows:

Initialize the model with a constant value, such as the mean of the target variable.

For each weak learner:

  • Train the weak learner on the training data.
  • Compute the predictions of the weak learner.
  • Compute the residual errors of the previous model by subtracting the predicted values from the actual values.
  • Fit the weak learner to the residual errors.
  • Update the weights of the training examples based on the fitted residual errors.
  • Combine the predictions of all the weak learners to make a final prediction.

The key idea behind Gradient Boosting is that by fitting the model to the residual errors of the previous model, it can focus on the examples that were not well predicted by the previous model and improve its overall accuracy.

The Gradient Boosting algorithm involves computing the negative gradient of the loss function with respect to the predicted values and using it to update the model. The equation for computing the negative gradient is:

$$\large Negative\ Gradient = -\frac{\partial L(y_\text{true}, y_\text{pred})}{\partial y_\text{pred}}$$

Here, $y_{true}$ is the true label of the example, $y_{pred}$ is the predicted value of the model, and the partial derivatives are taken with respect to these variables.

The weight of the weak learner is then computed as:

$$\large \alpha = learning\ rate * negative\ gradient$$

Finally, the model is updated as:

$$\large model\ prediction = model\ prediction + alpha * weak\ learner\ prediction$$

Here, learning_rate is a hyperparameter that controls the step size of each update, weak learner prediction is the prediction of the weak learner for the example, and the sum is over all the weak learners.

XGBoost Classifier¶

What is XGBoost?

XGBoost (short for Extreme Gradient Boosting) is a highly optimized implementation of the Gradient Boosting algorithm. It was developed by Tianqi Chen at the University of Washington and is widely used in data science competitions.

How does XGBoost work?

XGBoost works by sequentially adding weak learners to the model and updating the weights of the training examples based on the residual errors of the previous models. The algorithm is similar to Gradient Boosting, but includes several additional features to improve its performance:

Regularization:

XGBoost includes L1 and L2 regularization to prevent overfitting.

Tree Pruning: XGBoost includes a technique called "tree pruning" to remove irrelevant features and reduce the complexity of the model.

Weighted Quantile Sketch: XGBoost uses a weighted quantile sketch algorithm to speed up the computation of split points in the decision trees.

Conclusions:

The XGBoost algorithm involves computing the negative gradient of the loss function with respect to the predicted values and using it to update the model. The equation for computing the negative gradient is the same as in Gradient Boosting.

The weight of the weak learner is then computed as:

$$\large \alpha = learning\ rate * negative\ gradient + 0.5 * (L_1\ regularization + L_2\ regularization)$$

Finally, the model is updated.

Deep Learning¶

We adress the issue of overfitting by combining the following techniques:

  1. Regularization
  • We add regularization to our dense layers. We include L1 or L2 regularization to penalize large weights. The kernel_regularizer argument is thusly added to the Dense layers. The strenght is adjusted as needed
  1. Dropout
  • We add dropout layers
  1. Batch Normalization
  • We add batch normalization layers, which can help stabilize and accelerate the training of our deep neural networks.
  1. Early stopping
  • We implement early stopping to halt training when the model performance on a validation set stops improving. This can prevent overfitting by avoiding excessive training. Additionally, the EarlyStopping callback has been added to monitor the validation loss and stop training if the loss does not improve after a certain number of epochs (patience=5 in this example).
  1. Learning Rate Schedule
  • We fine-tune a learning schedule to slow down the learning rate as training progresses
  1. K-fold Cross-Validation
In [ ]:
# Set the number of folds
num_folds = 2

# Create a KFold object
kf = KFold(n_splits=num_folds, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

# Initialize a list to store accuracy values for each fold
accuracy_values = []
training_histories = []  # List to store training histories for each fold

# Iterate over folds
for train_index, val_index in kf.split(X_train):
    # Convert indices to lists
    train_index, val_index = list(train_index), list(val_index)

    # Split the data into training and validation sets for this fold
    X_fold_train, X_fold_val = X_train.iloc[train_index], X_train.iloc[val_index]
    y_fold_train, y_fold_val = y_train.iloc[train_index], y_train.iloc[val_index]


    # Build the MLP model for binary classification
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(Dense(4, input_dim=X_train.shape[1], kernel_regularizer=l2(1),activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())

    # Output layer with sigmoid activation for binary classification
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

    # Compile the model for binary classification
    lr_schedule = schedules.ExponentialDecay(initial_learning_rate=1e-1, decay_steps=1, decay_rate=0.5)
    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=lr_schedule), loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

    #early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=5, restore_best_weights=True)

    # Train the model and save the history
    history = model.fit(X_fold_train, y_fold_train, validation_data=(X_fold_val, y_fold_val),
                        epochs=4, batch_size=3, verbose=1)

    # Store the training history
    training_histories.append(history.history)

    # Predict on the validation set
    y_pred_val = model.predict(X_fold_val)
    y_pred_val_binary = (y_pred_val > 0.5).astype(int)

    # Evaluate the model on the validation set and store the accuracy
    accuracy_fold = accuracy_score(y_fold_val, y_pred_val_binary)
    accuracy_values.append(accuracy_fold)

# Calculate and print the average accuracy across all folds
average_accuracy = np.mean(accuracy_values)

print(f'Average Accuracy across {num_folds} folds: {average_accuracy}')

# Plot training and validation loss for each fold
for i, history in enumerate(training_histories):
    plt.plot(history['loss'], label=f'Fold {i+1} Training Loss')
    plt.plot(history['val_loss'], label=f'Fold {i+1} Validation Loss')

plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Summary¶

  1. Conversion likelihood is highly dependant on the company s website and application efficiency, more than on ad exposure of references.

  2. Age matters although we can suspect networks dynamics within individuals of the same age and not individual across age group.

  3. Occupation is not a good predictor of conversion.

  4. Completeness of profile does influence conversion positively although it is a by product of root predictors i.e., time spent on the website and number of website visits

Recommendations¶

Improve the mobile app and the website through:

  • Better Customer Onboarding. Provide only the essential information at the beginning of the customer experience.

  • Ergonomic and Simple Login Screen. Provide simple registration, allowing users to login from external accounts such as Facebook or Google. Only ask users for information that is needed.

  • Simple Menus and Navigation

  • Reduce Search Effort

  • Improve interface design

Those actionable insights will help the company attract more leads under 30 years old and its conversion rate in this demographic specifically through network effects (mobile app leverage), and its overall market coverage (website leverage).
